Hi Jeffrey, thanks for reporting this! 

I found this in the log:

```shell
Caused by: java.sql.SQLException: Does not support setReadOnly
        at org.apache.iotdb.jdbc.IoTDBConnection.setReadOnly(IoTDBConnection.java:319) ~[iotdb-jdbc-0.12.4.jar!/:0.12.4]
        at com.zaxxer.hikari.pool.PoolBase.setupConnection(PoolBase.java:372) ~[HikariCP-2.5.1.jar!/:na]
        at com.zaxxer.hikari.pool.PoolBase.newConnection(PoolBase.java:346) ~[HikariCP-2.5.1.jar!/:na]
        at com.zaxxer.hikari.pool.HikariPool.checkFailFast(HikariPool.java:506) ~[HikariCP-2.5.1.jar!/:na]
        ... 74 common frames omitted
```

Has the method `setReadOnly` ever been called by your application? The method is not supported by the `IoTDBConnection`. 

The IoTDB will automatically set the status to ReadOnly only in the event of a system failure. In other cases, we should not set the system state to read-only.

Hello Steve,

"My" application is Grafana 8.3.3. My setup consists of three Docker containers:

1. apache/iotdb:0.12.4-node
2. apache/iotdb:0.12.4-grafana (or as stated before [my own Option 2 iotdb-grafana installation](https://github.com/promouseus/open-field_time-series/blob/main/iotdb-grafana/Dockerfile))
3. [grafana/grafana:latest based container](https://github.com/promouseus/open-field_time-series/blob/main/grafana/Dockerfile) with the [data source configured](https://github.com/promouseus/open-field_time-series/blob/main/grafana/iotdb.yaml)

For testing I add some time-series with a bash script like this:
```
iotdbCli='docker exec -it iotdb /iotdb/sbin/start-cli.sh -h 127.0.0.1 -p 6667 -u root -pw root'
${iotdbCli} -e "set storage group to root.sentico"
${iotdbCli} -e "CREATE TIMESERIES root.sentico.portal.ipv4.\"10.20.20.254\".rtt WITH DATATYPE=FLOAT, ENCODING=RLE"
${iotdbCli} -e "CREATE TIMESERIES root.sentico.portal.ipv4.\"1.1.1.1\".rtt WITH DATATYPE=FLOAT, ENCODING=RLE"
```

And I create some data by running the following bash script a couple of times:
```
timestamp=`date +%s%3N`
rtt1=`ping 8.8.8.8 -qc1|tail -n 1|awk -F' ' '{print $4}'|awk -F'/' '{print $1}'`
rtt2=`ping 1.1.1.1 -qc1|tail -n 1|awk -F' ' '{print $4}'|awk -F'/' '{print $1}'`

${iotdbCli} -e "INSERT INTO root.sentico.portal.ipv4.\"10.20.20.254\"(timestamp,rtt) values(${timestamp},${rtt1})"
${iotdbCli} -e "INSERT INTO root.sentico.portal.ipv4.\"1.1.1.1\"(timestamp,rtt) values(${timestamp},${rtt2})"
```

Doing above for 0.12.3 and 0.12.4 results in the log file as supplied. If I leave container 1 (iotdb-node) and 3 (grafana) in tact and only change container 2 (iotdb-grafana) back to 0.12.2 everything is working immediately. So the problem seems isolated to the iotdb-grafana 0.12.3 and 0.12.4 version. For now I use iotdb-node 0.12.4 combined with iotdb-grafana 0.12.2 and that seems to work (at least in my basic tests).

If you need any more information or I can assist you with something, please let me know.

Cheers,

Jeffrey

> Could you please explain why? if remove the code here, will the single node not benefit from the cache? and the `cachedQueryDataSourcesMap` attribute seems do not used anywhere.

In [IOTDB-2101](https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/IOTDB-2101), we refactor the construction process of `QueryDataSource`. We let all sensors in one virtual sg share the same `QueryDataSource` to save memory.

In the standalone mode, we will call the `initQueryDataSource()` method to construct all the required `QueryDataSource` in this query and save it in `cachedQueryDataSourcesMap`.

But in the cluster mode, for some reason, we must construct a `QueryDataSource` for each series.

I will post more details about the construction and use of `QueryDataSource` to a confluence page later.
